\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:Introduction}

Over the past three decades, \textbf{credit derivatives} have become increasingly common tools for finanical institutions that wish to pass on \textbf{credit risk} to investors who accept that risk in exchange for interest. To put it simply, credit risk is the possibility that a borrower will \textbf{default} on her loan, or not pay it back. There are many types of credit derivatives, including collaterized debt obligations (CDOs) and collaterized loan obligations (CLOs). In this paper, we will focus on \textbf{credit default swaps} (CDS), a type of credit derivative that has become quite popular among pension funds, hedge funds, and investment banks, among other financial institutions. We will explain the mechanics of this financial product and show how this \textbf{CDS} package can be used to manipulate and calcuate relevant CDS information. 

CDS originated in the late 1980s and were popularized by a team at J.P. Morgan that included Blythe Masters \citep{cdsOrigins, blythe}. Many different types of CDS have since emerged including basket default swaps (BDSs), index CDS, credit-linked notes, etc. \citep{jk}. In this \textbf{CDS} package, we focus on calculations related to single-name, or corporate, credit default swaps.

\section{CDS Basics}
\label{sec:CDSBasics}

Consider the following example: there exists a portfolio manager---a manager of multiple investments---who has just bought \$100,000 worth of bonds from company X. We'll discuss what a bond is in a later section, but for now just think of it as an I.O.U.; the portfolio manager lends \$100,000 to company X for a certain time period, and at the end of the period, company X returns the \$100,000 to the manager. After she buys the bonds, however, her confidence in company X's ability to make good on its obligation and return the \$100,000 begins to waiver. What should she do? 

One popular option in today's economy is to enter a \textbf{credit default swap} (CDS) agreement with a third party. In this case, the portfolio manager could enter a CDS contract in which she pays a fee to the third party, and if company X can't pay back the sum of \$100,000, the third party will pay the remaining monetary amount. In other words, the portfolio manager pays a fee in exchange for protection against company X's inability to meet its obligation. 

\subsection{An Example: Property Insurance}
\label{sec:PropInsurance}

In order to understand this type of exchange, let's first talk about a simpler from of purchasing protection: property insurance. 

Suppose that an insurance company charges \$1,000 for one year of property insurance coverage. This \$1,000 is known as the \textbf{premium}. In exchange for this premium payment, the insurance company agrees to monetarily compensate for any property damage for the next year. Note that the two parties---insurance buyer and insurance company---would need to agree on what constitutes "property damage" in order to make this insurance agreement. For our example, let's assume that property damage only includes fire damage. 

Let's say that a person buys one year of property insurance on his house---a house worth \$200,000---and a house fire occurs on June 30 and damages half of the house. In such a scenario, the insurance company is obligated to pay \$100,000, or the worth of half the house, to the insurance buyer.

Let's assume that the premium is paid at the beginning of each calendar year, on January 1. Let's also assume that, in this case of property damage, the insurance company pays out the compensational amount at the end of the year (Decemeber 31), regardless of when the damage actually occured. Examining the cash flows in our example above, we can see that the insurance buyer pays a \$1,000 premium on January 1 for property insurance for that year, and the insurance company pays the buyer a compensational amount of \$100,000 on December 31. Note that if there was no house fire for that year, then the insurance company can pocket the \$1,000 premium payment, and not have to pay anything in return. Conversely, if the whole house burned down in a fire---instead of just half the house---then the insurance company would have to pay the buyer the full worth of the house: \$200,000.

As such, before making this deal, both parties would want to consider the probability of fire damage for that year. If, for example, the house owner was extremely confident that no house fire would occur, and thus believed the probability of fire damage to be essentially 0\%, then he would not want to make this deal. The only cash flow between the two parties would be the \$1,000 premium payment out of \emph{his} pocket for the one-year coverage! Simiarly, if the insurance company thought it was extremely likely that some part of the house would burn down---perhaps some of the house's electric circuits are outdated and inefficient---then the insurance company would probably not want to make this deal. In that case, the compensational payment for the fire damage would greatly outweigh the premuim payment, and the insurance company would acquire a net loss of money.

Consider that this is a house in which, as suggested before, half of the house's electric circuits are old and malfunctioning. For simplicity's sake, we can safely assume that if the house catches fire, the cause would be the outdated electrical circuits, and only half the house would be affected. In such a scenario, what probability of fire damage would make both parties agree to this deal? In other words, what probability of fire damage would render the \textbf{expected payment values} for both parties equal? 

To answer this question, we need to first determine the value that each party expects to pay. The insurance buyer expects to pay a \$1,000 premium on January 1, regardless of whether fire damage occurs or not. The insurance company's payment, however, depends on the occurence of fire damage. Thus, we can say the following: 

\vspace{-2em} 
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm Insurance\hspace{3pt}company's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}payment = (Probability\hspace{3pt}of\hspace{3pt}fire) * (Payment\hspace{3pt}in\hspace{3pt}case\hspace{3pt}of\hspace{3pt}fire)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation} 

Note, again, that we are assuming the expected payment in the case of fire to be \$100,000, the worth of one half of the house. To determine the "fair" probability of fire damage (we'll call it "p") at which both parties would agree to this deal, we set the expected payment values of each party equal to each other:  

\vspace{-2em} 
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm Insurance\hspace{3pt}buyer's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}payment = Insurance\hspace{3pt}company's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}payment}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm \$1,000 = {p} * {\$100,000}}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Thus, we can see that if "p" is .01, or 1\%, then this would be considered a fair deal for both parties; the expected payments are equal.

\subsection{Simple One-Period Case}
\label{sec:OnePeriod}

Instead of buying insurance against property damage, let's consider buying insurance against a company's inability to meet its obligations---like our example with the portfolio manager and company X. This time, our portfolio manager owns \$250,000 worth of bonds from Alcoa, a company, and she is concerned that Alcoa won't return the money she lent. In other words, she is concerned that Alcoa will \textbf{default} on its bonds---not pay them back---and that it may even go bankrupt in the next year. So, she enters a one-year CDS agreement with an investment bank---say, J.P. Morgan.

What does this mean? Well, for simplicity's sake, we'll keep the same numerical figures timeline (January 1 - December 31) from our property insurance example. The portfolio manager agrees to pay a \textbf{coupon} (equivalent to the premium in our property insurance example) of 1\% (equivalent to 100 basis points (bps)) of the face value of the bonds, also known as the \textbf{notional amount} in a CDS: \$100,000. Thus, the portfolio manager pays \$1,000 on January 1 in exchange for protection against default of Alcoa for that year. This side of the CDS contract is known as the \textbf{premium leg}, and the portfolio manager is known as the \textbf{protection buyer}. 

The other side of the CDS agreement is known as the \textbf{protection leg} and involves J.P. Morgan, the \textbf{protection seller}. Before delving into these cash flows, we first need to discuss what happens when a company defaults on its bonds and/or goes bankrupt. When this happens, the company's remaining assets are first allocated to its bondholders. The ratio of the amount a bondholder receives after a company's default compared to the amount the bondholder \emph{should} have received (with no default) is known as the \textbf{recovery rate}. For our example, if Alcoa's recovery rate is 40\%, then the portfolio manager would receive \$40,000 of the notional amount from Alcoa in the case of default. As such, similar to how the insurance company only had to compensate the insurance buyer with half the value of the house in the property insurance example, J.P. Morgan only has to pay \$60,000---not the entire notional amount---to the portfolio manager in the case of default, assuming the above recovery rate. Note that Alcoa is known as the \textbf{reference entity} in this CDS since it is the company from which the protection buyer desires protection.

%% \begin{figure}[H]
%% \centering
%% \includegraphics[width=4in, height=1in]{images/CDSmechanics.png}
%% \caption{Cash flows in a single-name CDS contract.}
%% \label{fig:cashFlow}
