Is this agreement a fair deal, given the assumptions mentioned above (40\% recovery rate, 1\% coupon, etc.)? Like in our property insurance example, we can determine this by looking at the expected payment for the portfolio manager and for J.P. Morgan. A fair deal means that these two values are equal. In the equation below, "r" signifies the recovery rate and "d" signifies the \textbf{probability of default}.

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm \$1,000 = {d} * (({1-r})*{\$100,000})}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Before we plug in 40\% for "r" to determine the value of "d", the probability of default that would render this agreement fair, let's discuss the above equation. The left side of the equation represents the expected payment of the protection buyer, which consists solely of the one coupon payment of \$1,000. The right side of the equation refers to the expected payment of the protection seller, which draws from the same logic as Equation 1 in the property insurance example.

\vspace{-2em}
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm Protection\hspace{3pt}seller's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}payment = (Probability\hspace{3pt}of\hspace{3pt}default)*(Payment\hspace{3pt}in\hspace{3pt}case\hspace{3pt}of\hspace{3pt}default)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Note that the only reason Equation 4 may look more complicated than Equation 5 is that the "Payment in case of default" has to take in the recovery rate; recall that we had a recovery rate of 40\% that covered \$40,000 of the notional amount, and thus the payment that J.P. Morgan had to make to the portfolio manager was \$60,000.

Now, back to finding the probability of default that gives a fair deal. When we plug in 40\% for "r" in Equation 4, we have the following:

\vspace{-2em}
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm \$1,000 = {d} * {\$60,000}}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Solving for "d", we get that the probability of default that would make this agreement fair is 1.667\% (rounded to two demical places).

\subsubsection{Accrued Interest}
\label{sec:AccruedInterest}

We have so far assumed that our CDS agreement between the portfolio manager and J.P. Morgan begins on January 1 and ends on December 31 of the same year. However, what if this agreement wasn't made exactly on January 1? What if it was made halfway through the year, on June 30? Let's assume the probability of default for those six months is indeed 1.667\%---the probability that renders the CDS contract fair. Under our current description of a CDS agreement, this implies that the portfolio manager would have to pay the same coupon of 1\% (\$1,000) on January 1 for only receiving six months (instead of one year) of protection coverage. Now, the expected payment of the portfolio manager is greater than that of J.P. Morgan.

To account for this, let's first calculate the amount of the coupon that the portfolio manager is unfairly paying---that is, the fraction of the coupon payment that accounts for the first six months of the year (January 1 - June 30), which she does not receive coverage for. This fraction of the coupon payment is known as the \textbf{accrued interest}.

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm Accrued = \frac{180}{360}*\frac{1.0}{100}*\$100,000 = \$500}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Note that we just divided the coupon payment in half, which makes sense since January 1 - June 30 consists of half of the year. Note also that we are dividing 180 by 360 instead of 365 in the above calculation. This particular CDS contract can be said to have a 30/365 \textbf{day count convention}, meaning that the accrued interest calculations are based on the assumptions that there are 30 days in a month and 360 days in a year. This simplication makes calculations much easier. 

%% Why, other than for simplicity's sake, do people use the 30/365 day count convention?

The portfolio manager does not want (and understandably does not have the obligation) to pay for the six months she did not receive coverage for. Instead, it is \emph{J.P. Morgan} who pays the accrued interest to the portfolio manager; after this adjustment, the expected payments from each party are once again equal. Since the portfolio manager is already paying J.P. Morgan a coupon of \$1,000 and now, in this case where the CDS contract initiates on June 30, J.P. Morgan owes the portfolio manager \$500 of accrued interest, the two parties can agree to one equivalent cash flow: \$500 from the portfolio manager to J.P. Morgan.

Note that accrued interest only becomes relevant when the contract does not initiate on a coupon payment date. In the real-world CDS market, there are four dates each year---instead of, in our example, the one date of January 1---when coupon payments can be made. These dates are known as \textbf{roll dates} and comprise the following: March 20, June 20, September 20, and December 20. As we proceed with our simple CDS example, however, we'll continue with the assumption that January 1 is the one and only "roll date."  

%% ACCRUED INTEREST + DISCOUNTED RATES + UPFRONT PAYMENTS: Thus, if the CDS contract was initiated on June 30, then the total upfront payment made by J.P. Morgan to the portfolio manager would be \$495 (which is equal to \$500/(1+ 1\%) rounded to nearest dollar) + \$250 = \$745. This value is known as the \textbf{dirty upfront}, since it specifies the actual upfront payment that (in this case) the protection seller will pay the protection buyer. The \textbf{clean upfront}, on the other hand, does not take accrued interest into account, and (in this case) is equal to \$495. Note that the portion of the upfront payment that accounts for a lower probability of default than 1\% is discounted by the discount rate, and the portion that accounts for the accured interest is not. This is because the accrued interest should be worth \$250 \emph{now} (June 30), and the other portion of the upfront payment should be worth \$500 on December 31.

\subsubsection{Upfront payment}
\label{sec:Upfront}

So far, we have assumed that the probability of default for our simple, one-period CDS example is indeed 1.667\%---the probability that renders the CDS contract fair. However, what if the chance of Alcoa's default is \emph{not} 1.667\%---what if it's 1\%? Clearly, this is no longer a fair deal. The expected payment of the portfolio manager---known as the \textbf{protection buyer} in the CDS agreement---at the end of the year will be greater than J.P. Morgan's expected payment since the probability of default (and thus the probility that J.P. Morgan will have to pay out any money at all) is less than the example above. A simple solution to this issue would be to lower the protection buyer's coupon to 0.6\% (or \$600), as portrayed below:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm \$1,000 = ({d = 1.667\%}) * {\$60,000}} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
When we change the probability of default from 1.667\% to 1.00\%, we can adjust the one-time coupon payment accordingly (\$1,000 to \$600), as that would be ideal. Note, that we have kept the "Payment in case of default" at \$60,000 because the notional amount is still \$100,000 and the recovery rate is still 40\%.
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm \$600 = ({d = 1.00\%}) * {\$60,000}} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

However, let's say that, by market convention, all CDS are traded at a standard coupon of 1\%. If the probability of Alcoa's default is less 1\% (0.6\% in this case), how do we modify the CDS agreement to once again make it a fair trade for both parties? (Note that we are, once again, considered a situation in which the CDS agreement initiates on January 1, not June 30. Thus, accrued interest is not a factor.)

The answer lies in an \textbf{upfront payment}---a payment made from one party to the other at the beginning of a contract (in this case, January 1). If the probability of Alcoa's default is 0.6\%, then J.P. Morgan has to compensate the protection buyer for paying a coupon of 1\% instead of a coupon of 0.6\%. Since the difference between the protection buyer's fair payment (\$600 at 0.6\%) and the payment she has to make due to regulations (\$1,000 at 1\%) is \$400, J.P. Morgan's upfront payment to the protection buyer should be \$400. In our case, we can also express the value of the upfront payment (rounded to the nearest dollar) in terms of this equation:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm Upfront\hspace{3pt}Payment = {\$60,000} * ({1.667\% - 1.00\%}) = \$400} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

%% Upfront payment = {1-r}{notional}*{(fair p)-(standard p)}
Note that we need to know what the probability of default is in order to calculate an upfront payment. Conversely, if we only know the upfront payment, we can calculate the implied probability of default that both parties agree to. 

That way, with an upfront payment, the two parties can trade according to CDS convention and still create a fair deal in which the expected payments from each party are equal. Let's assume that both the upfront payment and the coupon payment are made at the same time: on January 1, the first day of the one-year contract. In this case, since the portfolio manager would have to pay J.P. Morgan \$1,000, and J.P. Morgan would have to pay the buyer \$400, the two parties can just agree to have one equivalent cash flow: the protection buyer paying \$600 to J.P. Morgan.

